{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491314"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:42:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:42:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"909"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/909"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.1,0.43,0.22,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109044"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/909"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"909"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91410"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"175"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"2136"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1626"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11026"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19839"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35357"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39478"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40713"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109044"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner after experiencing intermittent right loin pain yesterday. The pain radiated into his groin and was so intense that he had to lie down and take some painkillers. He also noticed that his urine was pink coloured. He is now symptom-free. His medical history includes an incidental finding of an abdominal aortic aneurysm one year ago which measured \u00a03cm in diameter. He takes perindopril and atorvastatin for his high blood pressure and cholesterol which are appropriately controlled. He does not drink any alcohol. He has not smoked cigarettes for 5 years but smoked in the past (20 pack-year history..\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well and vital signs are within normal limits. The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable. The practitioner suspects a kidney stone and arranges a non-contrast CT. This does not show any renal tract pathology, however, his abdominal aortic aneurysm is noted to be at 3.5cm. He does have haematuria on urine microscopy\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate advice to give the patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and no further action","Reconstructed 3D CT angiography and outpatient review","Ultrasound examination of the aorta in three years","Repeat CT scan in one year","Urgent surgical opinion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAn abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) is the abnormal focal dilatation of the abdominal aorta. Common risk factors for AAA are smoking (most common), advanced age (ie, \u0026gt;60 years), atherosclerosis, male gender and connective tissue diseases. Most cases of AAA are asymptomatic. Patients with symptomatic AAA present with abdominal or back pain, or very occasionally lower limb pain due to distal embolisation. Although many studies have revealed a beneficial effect of screening for AAA, no screening protocol has been established in Australia despite being common in practice in other countries such as the UK. The management of AAA depends on the size, progression, and symptoms of the aneurysm. A very small AAA is very unlikely to cause these symptoms. Rare aortic pathologies such as a penetrating aortic ulcer or small saccular aneurysm should be excluded by the radiologist on the CT report.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough there is variation in the international guidelines for the surveillance of asymptomatic abdominal aortic aneurysms (AAAs), the 2024 European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) guidelines are most widely followed, including in Australia and New Zealand. The ESVS guidelines recommend the following monitoring schedule for asymptomatic patients according to AAA diameter:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E25 - 29 mm: ultrasound every five years\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E30 - 39 mm: ultrasound every three years \u003C/strong\u003E(appropriate in this case)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E40 - 49 mm (men) or 40 \u2013 44 mm (women): annual ultrasound\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u226550 mm (men) or \u226545 mm (women): ultrasound every six months.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u226555 mm (men) or \u226550 mm (women): most surgeons would consider offering surgical repair; note that the threshold for elective repair in women is lower due to higher rupture risk at smaller diameters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that these are general guidelines, and different monitoring protocols may be utilised for patients with AAAs based on clinician judgement and patient factors (e.g. life expectancy, suitability for future repair, patient preferences).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe benefit of an elective aneurysm repair is weighed with the risk of rupture. The indications for surgical management of AAA are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESize \u0026gt;55 mm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGrowth in size of \u0026gt;10 mm/year\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESymptomatic AAA\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, this patient does not fulfil any of the three indications for an\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent surgical opinion\u003C/strong\u003E, and therefore management with surveillance is sufficient.\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003Ewould be inadequate as he will require surveillance with an ultrasound.\u003Cstrong\u003E\u00a0Repeat CT in one year\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0is incorrect as surveillance is typically completed with an ultrasound, and in this case should be done in three year\u0027s time. The sudden intermittent loin pain is likely to be caused by kidney stones that have passed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReconstructed 3D CT angiography (CTA)\u00a0\u003C/strong\u003Eallows for detailed anatomic characterisation of the abdominal aortic aneurysm which can facilitate planning of endovascular repair. However, this should be considered following an urgent surgical referral.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Abdominal aortic aneurysm that are symptomatic, larger than 55 m/m and/or that grows \u003E10 mm per year should be referred for surgical management"],"references":["ESVS 2024 Clinical Practice Guidelines on the Management of Abdominal Aortic Aneurysm. In: European Society for Vascular Surgery (ESVS) [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://esvs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/ESVS-2024-AAA-Guidelines.pdf","Kent KC. Abdominal Aortic Aneurysms. N Engl J Med 2014;371:2101-08. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25427112/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91410"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"909"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91410"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"202